segments.text: It's real hard to just strike out, you know, and say we're going to do this, and it's hard
to explain, I think, to the average citizen how engineering research affects their lives
until you try to do is put it in what it is we do, and now it has an impact.
Isn't invent kind of targeted to the individual?
Exactly.
It doesn't matter where, you know, anybody, anywhere, you have an idea, and you send it
in, and it will be reviewed, and the success ratio in selection is very small, because
most things have been thought of before or have been done better already, but it gives
you an opportunity to find out for no charge if there's a potential for something that
will, we're primarily targeted at things that will create.
More jobs, and it's going to enhance the productivity or the product line of businesses already
in existence, and or create new businesses.
What is, how does the Research Foundation entail?
The Research Foundation is an entity that panels all of our federal companies.
To give you an example of what they, how they function, we cannot, we could buy a boat or
a vessel.
We could buy a boat for environmental engineering to use, to do their research with, but we
can't purchase the insurance.
State entities can't buy the insurance.
They just, well, if you try to insure all these buildings, you'd be able to build one
building a year from their premiums, and so it's a good fiscal policy, except under certain
circumstances, and so there is a need to have a vehicle that can do those kinds of things.
So they serve special purpose needs, and in the past, they have also, they've been able
to do a lot more than an awful lot of the proposal preparation and contract negotiations
for various.
And at one point, they were almost one of the cities.
They've been fairly well separated since the late 70s, haven't they?
As far as I know, they were, they were very distinct operations.
They have probably grown more.
A lot of the services, we are able to do easier, quicker, or better, or what we find, we have
to justify to the researchers.
That we're purchasing a service, you know, and we've got to make sure that the researcher
gets his money's worth, and the university, you know, that we're, we're being cost-effective.
During your short stint here, what has been the biggest topic?
Oh, I think the fact that the whole, and that it was much more aggressively tuned to serving
the staff.
We found that so many people, you know, they were, you know, they were, you know, they
were, you know, they were, you know, they were, you know, they were, you know, they
were watching, they were, you know, they were ants for so many people, we, T's have
been a passive organization.
Responsive, but passive, I think, and we found that many people who didn't know that it existed
and that it could provide statewide service might have been on the way to creating another
entity, and it was a state agency to do exactly what we were chartered to do, and so, with
that threat, or possibility, relates to what's happening neighbor, so, we have to appetite
and outperform it.
Right.
Yeah.
we realized that we really did exist, and we did have a state charter.
We were not just here to serve Texas A&M University,
and we were a college station.
We were here to serve the state of Texas, and we could do that here.
This is a good place to do it.
We just needed to be more open with state and public officials
in saying that we recognize our state charter.
Do you think there has been national emphasis before?
It has always been in securing contracts.
We've always worked on a national basis as far as LAIS
on meeting Air Force and DOD and those kinds of contacts.
But I think that Texas is in the long line.
We are what's going to happen in the next.
The problems that you address here are also the problems of the nation.
And so it's just...
We've become very focused by doing one most often duty.
Were there any particular critical turning points besides the report?
Was there a time that you felt TEAS was threatened because of these new...
I don't know if there was any particular piece of legislation that...
It didn't get quite as far as legislation,
but the governor's commission...
Governor Plymouth set up the Texas...
Early on, it got canceled.
But we'll do that later.
Porter went over to participate in the
Engineering Extension Service staff development conference.
And one of the speakers was Vic Arnold.
And he was quoted from part of the research that he had done
as director of the Texas 2000.
It stated that there is no state agency to do R&D.
And we're sitting over here doing...
We started TTI in with this event.
And we're doing about $24 million.
We're doing about $24 million worth of research per year.
And so we thought maybe we might need to go talk to this person
and let him know that we exist.
And so we did that.
And actually, as one of the recommendations initially,
they were going to recommend that there be a state agency created
to do research and development.
We were invited to make a presentation to
a subcommittee on research and development
for the Texas 2000.
This was Paul Thayer, while he was still president of LTV,
before he was president of the national chamber.
He went to some government position.
A.B.
Holliday.
Just a wide variety of people.
Harvey McManus.
A wide variety of people.
Told them what the Engineering Experiment Station did.
And described to them the concept of the event,
which was just then coming up
as a way to address the needs of the
Joe Globe on the street.
And dealing with the ideas,
how to spur entrepreneurism.
And how to get every person to see that there is a need for R&D
and can't have a good idea and somebody can't help it.
The final recommendation in the target 2000 report
was that there be,
that the Institute for Ventures and New Technology,
which changed names about six classes,
we had to tell them all the time,
tell them what we were calling it that week,
serve as a prototype.
For similar types of efforts.
And there wasn't a recommendation.
That's probably the closest that I...
Was there recognition by them that A&M existed for R&D?
Oh, well with the invent statement.
That was, that was a major.
These were people in Austin that had worked for YouTube before.
They went to work on this project.
They went back to work for R&D.
They went back to work for UT
as Director of Bureau of Business Research afterwards.
So it opened their eyes.
Is that the most successful period?
Well, I think getting invent passed.
I really don't think that people internally
had as much confidence as people externally.
That legislation would pass in a very hectic session.
And that funding would be...
We got a million dollars in a very, very tight fiscal biennium.
And the Legislative Budget Board didn't recommend any money for it.
Because they felt like the Legislature needed to say
this was something so new and so different
that they had to have the whole House and Senate vote on it.
To demonstrate that this was the expenditure of money for them.
Because it was...
It created a precedent that had not existed before.
There is state law that says you cannot spend money...
You can't give money to a project.
You couldn't invest in a project.
We had to invest for the public good.
And we had to then do...
Our legislation, what it really says is that we agree that
the Institute exists for the public good.
And even though it helps individual people,
that's going to benefit the state.
By creating more jobs?
Exactly.
And...
So that bill did not pass.
The session was over very shortly thereafter.
And at the last minute was added...
The money was added as a rider in the appropriate...
To give us money to operate that.
That was a major...
I'm trying to think if there had been a...
Here it's just one turning point after another.
I think that another turning point is
our working relationships and our cooperative agreements
as bill research centers.
So that that will be a milestone.
Is there a project that you think T should have pursued that they didn't?
Oh, there's a lot of them.
I mean, look at the...
No.
We're still finding ways to work with Mexico again.
Establish international.
And that just doesn't happen overnight.
When did that process begin?
Oh, again, I think that was a mindset that we all felt comfortable with.
And had it started before that time?
Well, there had been...
I think Vincent will tell you.
We're just now beginning to see the real importance of
recognizing we're in a global economy.
The effort you're making right now is within the continent.
You had made a comment about the role of T's in education.
Can you expand any more on what you think that role is
and how it has changed?
Well, we're evolving another...
I don't know if it will ever become a vision,
but it's a laboratory center called the Learning Technology Center.
And this is a way to link engineers and educators
to work on the question of how people learn.
And I think technology is a tool that...
I don't know that current theory
is transferable to technological tools.
I think you may learn very differently
using a terminal, using a video disk,
using...you may not have to be in a particular building.
You may not have to be in a particular place.
Those flexibilities can change the educational environment
and can change the whole educational process.
Many people in the public schools are adamant about it
because they aren't convinced it will do anything different.
Much of what's been produced so far
is not very good.
We're just on the verge of having any...
put together anything that doesn't want to just entertain you.
So, it's as close to basic research as I have found.
What about the role of the research
and the aerodynamic research?
Is there much interplay between those?
Well, I think that...
Let me see if I understand your question.
Are you interested in how technology impacts teaching,
dynamics, or... How research is going on at TEAS?
Is it used in classroom instruction?
Oh, sure.
You will find that 80% of our employees are faculty.
They're joint employees.
We just buy out their time.
And so, the things they learn in the laboratory
are immediately transferable to their classroom.
And in fact, in a lot of cases,
much of the work done in the laboratory
is done by the graduate students.
And so, it's a learning.
What I hope evolves with our research park
and what I think is going to happen
at the graduate level eventually,
especially in a technical way,
is like we have teaching hospitals
for medicine and veterinary medicine right now.
We have teaching companies
that come and locate in research parks
where not only do you have the laboratories
where you're doing whatever it is the company does,
but those become a learning mechanism
that the buildings may have classrooms built right into.
And the people who are in industry
also become the way down the road.
The research park that you're talking about,
how is that?
What is the status of that?
As far as I know,
they have selected the A&E firm,
architecture and engineering firm,
that's going to do the construction.
Streets, sewers, they've got to get all the utilities set up.
You wouldn't...
But they do have funding, too.
Is it state funding?
Well, it's available funding.
What they're going to do is,
you know, you wouldn't go buy a lot in a subdivision
if it didn't have a road,
if it didn't have a sewer,
if it didn't have water and utilities,
and you didn't know how much it cost.
So they're in the process of that.
But they have committed themselves,
TEAS has committed themselves to doing this?
Well, now it's the university
that's actually the person.
It's not going to be a TEAS?
No, we're connected to it
in that we're supportive of it,
but it's actually...
There's a vice chancellor
for the research park in Corberville,
so it's really a system project.
How have external events affected you?
Oh, I think that we're...
I think external events affect us
in that there are things that need to be done
in research areas that sometimes are easier
to, quote, unquote, sell
based upon what...
much more receptive to education.
Since Nation at Risk,
since the national reports come out,
since we've had the governor's report on...
That is a topic that will be,
hopefully, the legislature will be receptive to.
But they're receptive to their problems,
and what we try to do is anticipate
what the problems are
and already have research teams in place
or beginning... the beginnings of that put together
so that we can respond.
As they're... Our best bet is if we can anticipate
the problem before they do,
before they begin to feel,
so that we can respond by saying,
yes, we're working in that area,
here's what we can do for it.
So what we do...
We work in the future.
We work on things that haven't been done before.
That's Mars.
Figure out what it is next.
So you've done that with education, in terms of...
Are there any other things that you, you know,
have since appeared here?
Oh, pure space.
The space technology effort
and space exploitation and commercial effort.
But what we did,
we do program with what they have done,
what problems are,
where they see research going.
And a recurring theme, year before last,
was that there's going to be a renewed emphasis.
But with a different...
Not just in getting there and getting back,
but what do you do once you're there?
And so we begin to toward that area
and begin some planning.
It's been since then
that the president has come in.
We're going to have a station.
And that there has been private companies spring up
that are trying to go into business
because NASA's thinking about turning the shuttle over
to some private contractor
for commercial, you know, operation.
So that they anticipate it.
All we have to do a lot of times is...
Who do you listen to?
Researchers.
Yes and no.
People.
You can read, you know,
you can follow a chain of events.
If you think far enough...
You think that in itself is a skill to...
Oh yeah.
Yeah.
I read something recently that described it really well.
And this psychologist or sociologist said that
there are one-year people
and there are ten-year people and five-year people.
He said some people,
if you're a one-year person,
you can only think in one-year time frame.
And you think everybody else thinks that way too.
I have always, well for a long time,
I don't guess I was aware of it,
but for a long time I've known that I think of ideas
and can go ahead and get them in place.
But they may not be really implemented and used
for three, four, five, ten years.
And then come up with products for others.
Yeah, it just happens that, you know,
the...
The...
The use and application and receptivity to something.
But you've got to have all of those kinds of people.
You can't have all...
People that just think in ten-year terms.
You know what I mean?
Think way out there.
Or you wouldn't get today's problem.
That's my line.
What is your general assessment of that?
You want to start there
and then I'll ask the rest of them?
Oh, ease is a benefit
in that it is a place that
has the flexibility
to long-term ideas
and to short-range needs.
If a researcher comes in today and said,
boy, if I could just do this, this, and this,
then we'd have this research project
and this would really help where we're going.
It would help Texas A&M.
It's really... We don't see ourselves as separate and apart.
The people that work for us are both.
I think that's...
That's hard for administrators
that are in charge of academics
to realize sometimes.
We're not trying to fight over
who this person belongs to.
We're just trying to support good programs.
In fact, a lot of the programs
that TEAS has developed traditionally
have then become universal.
There are things like that
that initially were started by TEAS,
either because TEAS had fiscal capability
and flexibility, because it has a flexibility with this.
The university has not felt it.
And also, TEAS seems to me to be the place
that's been able to take,
yeah, let's try this.
We'll try cyclotron.
And then if it's not what we need,
well, you know, there have been a lot of things
that they've shut down.
But it's a place where you can...
That's what research...
I think it's given the state very recently
a capability and a...
They didn't have to waste energy, time, and resources.
They can draw upon something
they've been in place for over 70 years.
I think it will become more important
in the next 20 years
than it has in the past,
simply because if you will look at the scale,
you can almost see an upturn.
We have, in the last four years,
grown at over 25% per year.
Physically?
Physically.
There is a larger demand,
and there is going to be a larger need
for what in the future,
especially in Texas.
There needs to be a resource
for those industries to draw on,
for capable answers to questions,
working relationships, and also at 20 talent.
What is the value of T's
to basic science versus technology?
I'm not sure that there is a difference.
I'd be interested in your definition of difference.
I'm not sure there's a difference either.
Dr. Seeley is sure there's a difference,
and he hasn't been able to,
he hasn't been able to explain it to me
well enough for me to understand it either.
But to the extent that basic science
is the theory upon technology.
You've got to start it with a problem.
To me, that's it.
You have a problem,
then you're working on something that's applied.
I think there's research,
and there's development.
And I think that in the body of research,
it's very hard to tell.
Or generic.
Because you may be working on,
discover something that's very,
not intentionally, but you can't prevent that from you.
Also, you can be working to discover
things that are of benefit.
What you can say is,
this is the research part,
and this is the development.
Is T's involved in both?
T's was not involved in
as much as it might be
if it is a vehicle where
when you discover something.
Or we also are much more sophisticated
in our trying to be aware
of how that will benefit the researcher
in the universe.
An example is
protein recently or something that
there is a university
more secure.
Dan Davis negotiated
a contract licensing agreement.
And Jim is taking home
a minimum of $200,000 a year
for the next year.
And probably, the estimates on a max
would be $2 million a year.
That same amount of money
comes back to him.
But that's development.
And we help with that.
But the research is really important.
Some people have said
basic research is what you do.
Well, the pure science,
I think, versus the engineering,
I think, is...
In the end,
what I get from the survey,
I say, show me
what the difference is.
Because I can take him
into some laboratories.
The Zachry building,
there are far more pure science
than most of the things
you'll find in the chemistry.
They're physics.
They're solid-state electronics.
But that's...
It's back to the
interdisciplinary thing.
I don't know that.
Is there anything else
you'd like to add to this?
I should know
that I don't know
or that I haven't asked.
You will run across
the difficulty of calling it up
to give you the answer.
I don't know
all the answers,
but I can point you
in the right direction.
